# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: quantile-regression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] In probability theory, the **conditional expectation**, **conditional expected value**, or **conditional mean** of a random variable is its expected value evaluated with respect to the conditional probability distribution.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] If the random variable can take on only a finite number of values, the "conditions" are that the variable can only take on a subset of those values.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] More formally, in the case when the random variable is defined over a discrete probability space, the "conditions" are a partition of this probability space.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Depending on the context, the conditional expectation can be either a random variable or a function.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] The random variable is denoted $E(X\mid Y)$ analogously to conditional probability.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] The function form is either denoted $E(X\mid Y=y)$ or a separate function symbol such as $f(y)$ is introduced with the meaning $E(X\mid Y)=f(Y)$ .
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Consider the roll of a fair dice and let *A* = 1 if the number is even (i.e., 2, 4, or 6) and *A* = 0 otherwise.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Furthermore, let *B* = 1 if the number is prime (i.e., 2, 3, or 5) and *B* = 0 otherwise.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Suppose we have daily rainfall data (mm of rain each day) collected by a weather station on every day of the ten-year (3652-day) period from January 1, 1990, to December 31, 1999.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] The unconditional expectation of rainfall for an unspecified day is the average of the rainfall amounts for those 3652 days.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] The *conditional* expectation of rainfall for an otherwise unspecified day known to be (conditional on being) in the month of March, is the average of daily rainfall over all 310 days of the ten–year period that fall in March.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Similarly, the conditional expectation of rainfall conditional on days dated March 2 is the average of the rainfall amounts that occurred on the ten days with that specific date.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] The related concept of conditional probability dates back at least to Laplace, who calculated conditional distributions.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] It was Andrey Kolmogorov who, in 1933, formalized it using the Radon–Nikodym theorem.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Doob from 1953, conditional expectation was generalized to its modern definition using sub-*σ*-algebras.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] where the sum is taken over all possible outcomes of X.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] If $P(A)=0$ , the conditional expectation is undefined due to the division by zero.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] where $P(X=x,Y=y)$ is the joint probability mass function of X and Y.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] The sum is taken over all possible outcomes of X.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] As above, the expression is undefined if $P(Y=y)=0$ .
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] When the denominator is zero, the expression is undefined.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Conditioning on a continuous random variable is not the same as conditioning on the event $\{Y=y\}$ as it was in the discrete case.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] For a discussion, see Conditioning on an event of probability zero.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Not respecting this distinction can lead to contradictory conclusions as illustrated by the Borel-Kolmogorov paradox.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] All random variables in this section are assumed to be in $L^{2}$ , that is square integrable.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] In its full generality, conditional expectation is developed without this assumption, see below under Conditional expectation with respect to a sub-*σ*-algebra.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] The $L^{2}$ theory is, however, considered more intuitive and admits important generalizations.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] In the context of $L^{2}$ random variables, conditional expectation is also called regression.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] In what follows let $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},P)$ be a probability space, and $X:\Omega \to \mathbb {R}$ in $L^{2}$ with mean $\mu _{X}$ and variance $\sigma _{X}^{2}$ .
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] The conditional expectation of X is defined analogously, except instead of a single number $\mu _{X}$ , the result will be a function $e_{X}(y)$ .
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Let $Y:\Omega \to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ be a random vector.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Note that unlike $\mu _{X}$ , the conditional expectation $e_{X}$ is not generally unique: there may be multiple minimizers of the mean squared error.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] In the context of linear regression, this lack of uniqueness is called multicollinearity.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Conditional expectation is unique up to a set of measure zero in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] The measure used is the pushforward measure induced by Y.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] In the first example, the pushforward measure is a Dirac distribution at 1.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] In the second it is concentrated on the "diagonal" $\{y:y_{2}=2y_{1}\}$ , so that any set not intersecting it has measure 0.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] The existence of a minimizer for $\min _{g}\operatorname {E} \left((X-g(Y))^{2}\right)$ is non-trivial.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] is a closed subspace of the Hilbert space $L^{2}(\Omega )$ .
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] In words, this equation says that the residual $X-e_{X}(Y)$ is orthogonal to the space M of all functions of Y.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] This orthogonality condition, applied to the indicator functions $f(Y)=1_{Y\in H}$ , is used below to extend conditional expectation to the case that X and Y are not necessarily in $L^{2}$ .
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] The conditional expectation is often approximated in applied mathematics and statistics due to the difficulties in analytically calculating it, and for interpolation.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] defined above is replaced with subsets thereof by restricting the functional form of g, rather than allowing any measurable function.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Examples of this are decision tree regression when g is required to be a simple function, linear regression when g is required to be affine, etc.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] These generalizations of conditional expectation come at the cost of many of its properties no longer holding.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] For example, let M be the space of all linear functions of Y and let ${\mathcal {E}}_{M}$ denote this generalized conditional expectation/ $L^{2}$ projection.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] If M does not contain the constant functions, the tower property $\operatorname {E} ({\mathcal {E}}_{M}(X))=\operatorname {E} (X)$ will not hold.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] An important special case is when X and Y are jointly normally distributed.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] for coefficients $\{\alpha _{i}\}_{i=0..n}$ described in Multivariate normal distribution#Conditional distributions.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] However, the local averages ${\textstyle \int _{H}X\,dP}$ can be recovered in $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {H}},P|_{\mathcal {H}})$ with the help of the conditional expectation.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] The existence of $\operatorname {E} (X\mid {\mathcal {H}})$ can be established by noting that ${\textstyle \mu ^{X}\colon F\mapsto \int _{F}X\,\mathrm {d} P}$ for $F\in {\mathcal {F}}$ is a finite measure on $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}})$ that is absolutely continuous with respect to P .
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] If h is the natural injection from ${\mathcal {H}}$ to ${\mathcal {F}}$ , then $\mu ^{X}\circ h=\mu ^{X}|_{\mathcal {H}}$ is the restriction of $\mu ^{X}$ to ${\mathcal {H}}$ and $P\circ h=P|_{\mathcal {H}}$ is the restriction of P to ${\mathcal {H}}$ .
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] where the derivatives are Radon–Nikodym derivatives of measures.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] It can be shown that they form a Markov kernel, that is, for almost all $\omega$ , $\kappa _{\mathcal {H}}(\omega ,-)$ is a probability measure.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] This shows that conditional expectations are, like their unconditional counterparts, integrations, against a conditional measure.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] In this setting the conditional expectation is sometimes also denoted in operator notation as $\operatorname {E} ^{\mathcal {H}}X$ .
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] All the following formulas are to be understood in an almost sure sense.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] All random variables here are assumed without loss of generality to be non-negative.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] The general case can be treated with $X=X^{+}-X^{-}$ .
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Any simple function is a finite linear combination of indicator functions.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] By linearity the above property holds for simple functions: if $X_{n}$ is a simple function then $E(X_{n}Y\mid {\mathcal {H}})=X_{n}\,E(Y\mid {\mathcal {H}})$ .
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Now let X be ${\mathcal {H}}$ -measurable.
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Then there exists a sequence of simple functions $\{X_{n}\}_{n\geq 1}$ converging monotonically (here meaning $X_{n}\leq X_{n+1}$ ) and pointwise to X .
[src:quantile-regression/conditional-expectation] Consequently, for $Y\geq 0$ , the sequence $\{X_{n}Y\}_{n\geq 1}$ converges monotonically and pointwise to $XY$ .
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Suppose that the data set consists of the points (*x**i*, *y**i*) with *i* = 1, 2, ..., *n*.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] To attain this goal, we suppose that the function *f* is of a particular form containing some parameters that need to be determined.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] For instance, the simplest form would be linear: *f*(*x*) = *bx* + *c*, where *b* and *c* are parameters whose values are not known but which we would like to estimate.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Less simply, suppose that *f*(*x*) is quadratic, meaning that *f*(*x*) = *ax*2 + *bx* + *c*, where *a*, *b* and *c* are not yet known.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Though the idea of least absolute deviations regression is just as straightforward as that of least squares regression, the least absolute deviations line is not as simple to compute efficiently.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Unlike least squares regression, least absolute deviations regression does not have an analytical solving method.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Therefore, an iterative approach is required.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] The following is an enumeration of some least absolute deviations solving methods.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Simplex-based methods are the “preferred” way to solve the least absolute deviations problem.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] A Simplex method is a method for solving a problem in linear programming.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] The most popular algorithm is the Barrodale-Roberts modified Simplex algorithm.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] The algorithms for IRLS, Wesolowsky's Method, and Li's Method can be found in Appendix A of among other methods.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Checking all combinations of lines traversing any two (x,y) data points is another method of finding the least absolute deviations line.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Since it is known that at least one least absolute deviations line traverses at least two data points, this method will find a line by comparing the SAE (Smallest Absolute Error over data points) of each line, and choosing the line with the smallest SAE.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] In addition, if multiple lines have the same, smallest SAE, then the lines outline the region of multiple solutions.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Though simple, this final method is inefficient for large sets of data.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] The problem can be solved using any linear programming technique on the following problem specification.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] with respect to the choice of the values of the parameters $a_{0},\ldots ,a_{k}$ , where *y**i* is the value of the *i*th observation of the dependent variable, and *x**ij* is the value of the *i*th observation of the *j*th independent variable (*j* = 1,...,*k*).
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] These constraints have the effect of forcing each $u_{i}$ to equal $|y_{i}-a_{0}-a_{1}x_{i1}-a_{2}x_{i2}-\cdots -a_{k}x_{ik}|$ upon being minimized, so the objective function is equivalent to the original objective function.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Since this version of the problem statement does not contain the absolute value operator, it is in a format that can be solved with any linear programming package.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] There exist other unique properties of the least absolute deviations line.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] In the case of a set of (*x*,*y*) data, the least absolute deviations line will always pass through at least two of the data points, unless there are multiple solutions.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] If multiple solutions exist, then the region of valid least absolute deviations solutions will be bounded by at least two lines, each of which passes through at least two data points.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] More generally, if there are *k* regressors (including the constant), then at least one optimal regression surface will pass through *k* of the data points.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] This "latching" of the line to the data points can help to understand the "instability" property: if the line always latches to at least two points, then the line will jump between different sets of points as the data points are altered.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] One known case in which multiple solutions exist is a set of points symmetric about a horizontal line, as shown in Figure A below.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] To understand why there are multiple solutions in the case shown in Figure A, consider the pink line in the green region.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Its sum of absolute errors is some value S.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] If one were to tilt the line upward slightly, while still keeping it within the green region, the sum of errors would still be S.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] It would not change because the distance from each point to the line grows on one side of the line, while the distance to each point on the opposite side of the line diminishes by exactly the same amount.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Thus the sum of absolute errors remains the same.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Also, since one can tilt the line in infinitely small increments, this also shows that if there is more than one solution, there are infinitely many solutions.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] The following is a table contrasting some properties of the method of least absolute deviations with those of the method of least squares (for non-singular problems).
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] The method of least absolute deviations finds applications in many areas, due to its robustness compared to the least squares method.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Least absolute deviations is robust in that it is resistant to outliers in the data.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] LAD gives equal emphasis to all observations, in contrast to ordinary least squares (OLS) which, by squaring the residuals, gives more weight to large residuals, that is, outliers in which predicted values are far from actual observations.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] This may be helpful in studies where outliers do not need to be given greater weight than other observations.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] If it is important to give greater weight to outliers, the method of least squares is a better choice.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] If in the sum of the absolute values of the residuals one generalises the absolute value function to a tilted absolute value function, which on the left half-line has slope $\tau -1$ and on the right half-line has slope $\tau$ , where $0<\tau <1$ , one obtains quantile regression.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] The case of $\tau =1/2$ gives the standard regression by least absolute deviations and is also known as *median regression*.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] where $\mathbf {\beta }$ is a column vector of coefficients to be estimated, *b* is an intercept to be estimated, **x****i** is a column vector of the *i*th observations on the various explanators, *y**i* is the *i*th observation on the dependent variable, and *k* is a known constant.
[src:quantile-regression/least-absolute-deviations] Regularization with LASSO (least absolute shrinkage and selection operator) may also be combined with LAD.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The **median** of a set of numbers is the value separating the higher half from the lower half of a data sample, a population, or a probability distribution.
[src:quantile-regression/median] For a data set, it may be thought of as the "middle" value.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The basic feature of the median in describing data compared to the mean (often simply described as the "average") is that it is not skewed by a small proportion of extreme values, and therefore provides a better representation of the center.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Median income, for example, may be a better way to describe the center of the income distribution because increases in the largest incomes alone have no effect on the median.
[src:quantile-regression/median] For this reason, the median is of central importance in robust statistics.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Median is a 2-quantile; it is the value that partitions a set into two equal parts.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The median of a finite list of numbers is the middle number when the numbers are arranged in order from smallest to greatest.
[src:quantile-regression/median] If the data set has an odd number of observations, the middle one is selected (after arranging in ascending order).
[src:quantile-regression/median] has the median of *6*, which is the fourth value.
[src:quantile-regression/median] If the data set has an even number of observations, there is no distinct middle value and the median is usually defined to be the arithmetic mean of the two middle values.
[src:quantile-regression/median] (In more technical terms, this interprets the median as the fully trimmed mid-range).
[src:quantile-regression/median] Formally, a median of a population is any value such that at least half of the population is less than or equal to the proposed median and at least half is greater than or equal to the proposed median.
[src:quantile-regression/median] As seen above, medians may not be unique.
[src:quantile-regression/median] If each set contains more than half the population, then some of the population is exactly equal to the unique median.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The median is well-defined for any ordered (one-dimensional) data and is independent of any distance metric.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The median can thus be applied to student grades that are ranked but not numerical (e.g. working out a median grade when student test scores are graded from F to A).
[src:quantile-regression/median] The result might be halfway between grades if there is an even number of students; for an odd number students, one specific grade is determined as the median.
[src:quantile-regression/median] A geometric median, on the other hand, is defined in any number of dimensions.
[src:quantile-regression/median] A related concept, in which the outcome is forced to correspond to a member of the sample, is the medoid.
[src:quantile-regression/median] There is no widely accepted standard notation for the median, but some authors represent the median of a variable *x* as med(*x*), *x͂*, as *μ*1/2, or as *M*.
[src:quantile-regression/median] In any of these cases, the use of these or other symbols for the median needs to be explicitly defined when they are introduced.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The median is a special case of other ways of summarizing the typical values associated with a statistical distribution: it is the 2nd quartile, 5th decile, and 50th percentile.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The median can be used as a measure of location when one attaches reduced importance to extreme values, typically because a distribution is skewed, extreme values are not known, or outliers are untrustworthy, i.e., may be measurement or transcription errors.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The median is 2 in this case, as is the mode, and it might be seen as a better indication of the center than the arithmetic mean of 4, which is larger than all but one of the values.
[src:quantile-regression/median] However, the widely cited empirical relationship that the mean is shifted "further into the tail" of a distribution than the median is not generally true.
[src:quantile-regression/median] At most, one can say that the two statistics cannot be "too far" apart; see § Inequality relating means and medians below.
[src:quantile-regression/median] As a median is based on the middle data in a set, it is not necessary to know the value of extreme results in order to calculate it.
[src:quantile-regression/median] For example, in a psychology test investigating the time needed to solve a problem, if a small number of people failed to solve the problem at all in the given time a median can still be calculated.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Because the median is simple to understand and easy to calculate, while also a robust approximation to the mean, the median is a popular summary statistic in descriptive statistics.
[src:quantile-regression/median] In this context, there are several choices for a measure of variability: the range, the interquartile range, the mean absolute deviation, and the median absolute deviation.
[src:quantile-regression/median] For practical purposes, different measures of location and dispersion are often compared on the basis of how well the corresponding population values can be estimated from a sample of data.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The median, estimated using the sample median, has good properties in this regard.
[src:quantile-regression/median] While it is not usually optimal if a given population distribution is assumed, its properties are always reasonably good.
[src:quantile-regression/median] For example, a comparison of the efficiency of candidate estimators shows that the sample mean is more statistically efficient when—and only when— data is uncontaminated by data from heavy-tailed distributions or from mixtures of distributions.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Even then, the median has a 64% efficiency compared to the minimum-variance mean (for large normal samples), which is to say the variance of the median will be ~50% greater than the variance of the mean.
[src:quantile-regression/median] An equivalent phrasing uses the cumulative distribution function $F\colon \,\mathbb {R} \to \mathbb {R}$ of $X\colon$ $\lim _{x\to m-}F(x)\leq {\frac {1}{2}}\leq F(m)$ (cf. the drawing in the definition of expected value for arbitrary real-valued random variables).
[src:quantile-regression/median] Note that this definition does not require *X* to have an absolutely continuous distribution (which has a probability density function *f*), nor does it require a discrete one.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Any probability distribution on the real number set $\mathbb {R}$ has at least one median, but in pathological cases there may be more than one median: if *F* is constant 1/2 on an interval (so that *f* = 0 there), then any value of that interval is a median.
[src:quantile-regression/median] In particular, if *m* is a sample median, then it minimizes the arithmetic mean of the absolute deviations.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Note, however, that in cases where the sample contains an even number of elements, this minimizer is not unique.
[src:quantile-regression/median] This optimization-based definition of the median is useful in statistical data-analysis, for example, in *k*-medians clustering.
[src:quantile-regression/median] If the distribution has finite variance, then the distance between the median ${\tilde {X}}$ and the mean ${\bar {X}}$ is bounded by one standard deviation.
[src:quantile-regression/median] This bound was proved by Book and Sher in 1979 for discrete samples, and more generally by Page and Murty in 1982.
[src:quantile-regression/median] In a comment on a subsequent proof by O'Cinneide, Mallows in 1991 presented a compact proof that uses Jensen's inequality twice, as follows.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The first and third inequalities come from Jensen's inequality applied to the absolute-value function and the square function, which are each convex.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The second inequality comes from the fact that a median minimizes the absolute deviation function $a\mapsto \operatorname {E} [|X-a|]$ .
[src:quantile-regression/median] where *m* is a spatial median, that is, a minimizer of the function $a\mapsto \operatorname {E} (\|X-a\|).\,$ The spatial median is unique when the data-set's dimension is two or more.
[src:quantile-regression/median] An alternative proof uses the one-sided Chebyshev inequality; it appears in an inequality on location and scale parameters.
[src:quantile-regression/median] This formula also follows directly from Cantelli's inequality.
[src:quantile-regression/median] A typical heuristic is that positively skewed distributions have mean > median.
[src:quantile-regression/median] This is true for all members of the Pearson distribution family.
[src:quantile-regression/median] For example, the Weibull distribution family has members with positive mean, but mean < median.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Violations of the rule are particularly common for discrete distributions.
[src:quantile-regression/median] For example, any Poisson distribution has positive skew, but its mean < median whenever $\mu {\bmod {1}}>\ln 2$ .
[src:quantile-regression/median] When the distribution has a monotonically decreasing probability density, the median is less than the mean, as shown in the figure.
[src:quantile-regression/median] This inequality generalizes to the median as well.
[src:quantile-regression/median] $f^{-1}\left(\,(-\infty ,t]\,\right)=\{x\in \mathbb {R} \mid f(x)\leq t\}$ is a closed interval (allowing the degenerate cases of a single point or an empty set).
[src:quantile-regression/median] Every convex function is a C function, but the reverse does not hold.
[src:quantile-regression/median] If the medians are not unique, the statement holds for the corresponding suprema.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Even though comparison-sorting *n* items requires Ω(*n* log *n*) operations, selection algorithms can compute the kth-smallest of n items with only Θ(*n*) operations.
[src:quantile-regression/median] This includes the median, which is the ⁠*n*/2⁠th order statistic (or for an even number of samples, the arithmetic mean of the two middle order statistics).
[src:quantile-regression/median] Selection algorithms still have the downside of requiring Ω(*n*) memory, that is, they need to have the full sample (or a linear-sized portion of it) in memory.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Because this, as well as the linear time requirement, can be prohibitive, several estimation procedures for the median have been developed.
[src:quantile-regression/median] A simple one is the median of three rule, which estimates the median as the median of a three-element subsample; this is commonly used as a subroutine in the quicksort sorting algorithm, which uses an estimate of its input's median.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The *remedian* is an estimator for the median that requires linear time but sub-linear memory, operating in a single pass over the sample.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The distributions of both the sample mean and the sample median were determined by Laplace.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Laplace's result is now understood as a special case of the asymptotic distribution of arbitrary quantiles.
[src:quantile-regression/median] We take the sample size to be an odd number $N=2n+1$ and assume our variable continuous; the formula for the case of discrete variables is given below in § Empirical local density.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The sample can be summarized as "below median", "at median", and "above median", which corresponds to a trinomial distribution with probabilities $F(v)$ , $f(v)$ and $1-F(v)$ .
[src:quantile-regression/median] Hence the density function of the median is a symmetric beta distribution pushed forward by F .
[src:quantile-regression/median] Its mean, as we would expect, is 0.5 and its variance is $1/(4(N+2))$ .
[src:quantile-regression/median] The additional 2 is negligible in the limit.
[src:quantile-regression/median] In practice, the functions f and F above are often not known or assumed.
[src:quantile-regression/median] However, they can be estimated from an observed frequency distribution.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Because the observations are discrete-valued, constructing the exact distribution of the median is not an immediate translation of the above expression for $\Pr(\operatorname {med} =v)$ ; one may (and typically does) have multiple instances of the median in one's sample.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Here, *i* is the number of points strictly less than the median and *k* the number strictly greater.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Using these preliminaries, it is possible to investigate the effect of sample size on the standard errors of the mean and median.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The observed mean is 3.16, the observed raw median is 3 and the observed interpolated median is 3.174.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The following table gives some comparison statistics.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The expected value of the median falls slightly as sample size increases while, as would be expected, the standard errors of both the median and the mean are proportionate to the inverse square root of the sample size.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The asymptotic approximation errs on the side of caution by overestimating the standard error.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The value of $(2f(x))^{-2}$ —the asymptotic value of $n^{-1/2}(\nu -m)$ where $\nu$ is the population median—has been studied by several authors.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The standard "delete one" jackknife method produces inconsistent results.
[src:quantile-regression/median] An alternative—the "delete k" method—where k grows with the sample size has been shown to be asymptotically consistent.
[src:quantile-regression/median] This method may be computationally expensive for large data sets.
[src:quantile-regression/median] A bootstrap estimate is known to be consistent, but converges very slowly (order of $n^{-{\frac {1}{4}}}$ ).
[src:quantile-regression/median] Other methods have been proposed but their behavior may differ between large and small samples.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The efficiency of the sample median, measured as the ratio of the variance of the mean to the variance of the median, depends on the sample size and on the underlying population distribution.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The efficiency tends to ${\frac {2}{\pi }}$ as N tends to infinity.
[src:quantile-regression/median] For univariate distributions that are *symmetric* about one median, the Hodges–Lehmann estimator is a robust and highly efficient estimator of the population median.
[src:quantile-regression/median] If data is represented by a statistical model specifying a particular family of probability distributions, then estimates of the median can be obtained by fitting that family of probability distributions to the data and calculating the theoretical median of the fitted distribution.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Pareto interpolation is an application of this when the population is assumed to have a Pareto distribution.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Previously, this article discussed the univariate median, when the sample or population had one-dimension.
[src:quantile-regression/median] When the dimension is two or higher, there are multiple concepts that extend the definition of the univariate median; each such multivariate median agrees with the univariate median when the dimension is exactly one.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The marginal median is defined for vectors defined with respect to a fixed set of coordinates.
[src:quantile-regression/median] A marginal median is defined to be the vector whose components are univariate medians.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The marginal median is easy to compute, and its properties were studied by Puri and Sen.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The geometric median of a discrete set of sample points $x_{1},\ldots x_{N}$ in a Euclidean space is the point minimizing the sum of distances to the sample points.
[src:quantile-regression/median] In contrast to the marginal median, the geometric median is equivariant with respect to Euclidean similarity transformations such as translations and rotations.
[src:quantile-regression/median] If the marginal medians for all coordinate systems coincide, then their common location may be termed the "median in all directions".
[src:quantile-regression/median] This concept is relevant to voting theory on account of the median voter theorem.
[src:quantile-regression/median] When it exists, the median in all directions coincides with the geometric median (at least for discrete distributions).
[src:quantile-regression/median] In statistics and computational geometry, the notion of centerpoint is a generalization of the median to data in higher-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Given a set of points in *d*-dimensional space, a centerpoint of the set is a point such that any hyperplane that goes through that point divides the set of points in two roughly equal subsets: the smaller part should have at least a 1/(*d* + 1) fraction of the points.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Like the median, a centerpoint need not be one of the data points.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Every non-empty set of points (with no duplicates) has at least one centerpoint.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The conditional median occurs in the setting where we seek to estimate a random variable X from a random variable Y , which is a noisy version of X .
[src:quantile-regression/median] For example, a popular model is $Y=X+Z$ where Z is standard normal independent of X .
[src:quantile-regression/median] It is known that for the model $Y=X+Z$ where Z is standard normal independent of X , the estimator is linear if and only if X is Gaussian.
[src:quantile-regression/median] When dealing with a discrete variable, it is sometimes useful to regard the observed values as being midpoints of underlying continuous intervals.
[src:quantile-regression/median] An example of this is a Likert scale, on which opinions or preferences are expressed on a scale with a set number of possible responses.
[src:quantile-regression/median] If the scale consists of the positive integers, an observation of 3 might be regarded as representing the interval from 2.50 to 3.50.
[src:quantile-regression/median] It is possible to estimate the median of the underlying variable.
[src:quantile-regression/median] If, say, 22% of the observations are of value 2 or below and 55.0% are of 3 or below (so 33% have the value 3), then the median m is 3 since the median is the smallest value of x for which $F(x)$ is greater than a half.
[src:quantile-regression/median] But the interpolated median is somewhere between 2.50 and 3.50.
[src:quantile-regression/median] First we add half of the interval width w to the median to get the upper bound of the median interval.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Then we subtract that proportion of the interval width which equals the proportion of the 33% which lies above the 50% mark.
[src:quantile-regression/median] In other words, we split up the interval width pro rata to the numbers of observations.
[src:quantile-regression/median] In this case, the 33% is split into 28% below the median and 5% above it so we subtract 5/33 of the interval width from the upper bound of 3.50 to give an interpolated median of 3.35.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The Hodges–Lehmann estimator has been generalized to multivariate distributions.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The Theil–Sen estimator is a method for robust linear regression based on finding medians of slopes.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The median filter is an important tool of image processing, that can effectively remove any salt-and-pepper noise from grayscale images.
[src:quantile-regression/median] In cluster analysis, the k-medians clustering algorithm provides a way of defining clusters, in which the criterion of maximising the distance between cluster-means that is used in k-means clustering, is replaced by maximising the distance between cluster-medians.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The idea dates back to Wald in 1940 who suggested dividing a set of bivariate data into two halves depending on the value of the independent parameter x : a left half with values less than the median and a right half with values greater than the median.
[src:quantile-regression/median] He suggested taking the means of the dependent y and independent x variables of the left and the right halves and estimating the slope of the line joining these two points.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The line could then be adjusted to fit the majority of the points in the data set.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Nair and Shrivastava in 1942 suggested a similar idea but instead advocated dividing the sample into three equal parts before calculating the means of the subsamples.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Brown and Mood in 1951 proposed the idea of using the medians of two subsamples rather the means.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Tukey combined these ideas and recommended dividing the sample into three equal size subsamples and estimating the line based on the medians of the subsamples.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Any *mean*-unbiased estimator minimizes the risk (expected loss) with respect to the squared-error loss function, as observed by Gauss.
[src:quantile-regression/median] A *median*-unbiased estimator minimizes the risk with respect to the absolute-deviation loss function, as observed by Laplace.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Other loss functions are used in statistical theory, particularly in robust statistics.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The theory of median-unbiased estimators was revived by George W.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Further properties of median-unbiased estimators have been reported.
[src:quantile-regression/median] There are methods of constructing median-unbiased estimators that are optimal (in a sense analogous to the minimum-variance property for mean-unbiased estimators).
[src:quantile-regression/median] Such constructions exist for probability distributions having monotone likelihood-functions.
[src:quantile-regression/median] One such procedure is an analogue of the Rao–Blackwell procedure for mean-unbiased estimators: The procedure holds for a smaller class of probability distributions than does the Rao—Blackwell procedure but for a larger class of loss functions.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Scientific researchers in the ancient near east appear not to have used summary statistics altogether, instead choosing values that offered maximal consistency with a broader theory that integrated a wide variety of phenomena.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Within the Mediterranean (and, later, European) scholarly community, statistics like the mean are fundamentally a medieval and early modern development.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The idea of the median appeared in the 6th century in the Talmud, in order to fairly analyze divergent appraisals.
[src:quantile-regression/median] However, the concept did not spread to the broader scientific community.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Instead, the closest ancestor of the modern median is the mid-range, invented by Al-Biruni Transmission of his work to later scholars is unclear.
[src:quantile-regression/median] He applied his technique to assaying currency metals, but, after he published his work, most assayers still adopted the most unfavorable value from their results, lest they appear to cheat.
[src:quantile-regression/median] However, increased navigation at sea during the Age of Discovery meant that ship's navigators increasingly had to attempt to determine latitude in unfavorable weather against hostile shores, leading to renewed interest in summary statistics.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Whether rediscovered or independently invented, the mid-range is recommended to nautical navigators in Harriot's "Instructions for Raleigh's Voyage to Guiana, 1595".
[src:quantile-regression/median] The idea of the median may have first appeared in Edward Wright's 1599 book *Certaine Errors in Navigation* on a section about compass navigation.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Wright was reluctant to discard measured values, and may have felt that the median — incorporating a greater proportion of the dataset than the mid-range — was more likely to be correct.
[src:quantile-regression/median] However, Wright did not give examples of his technique's use, making it hard to verify that he described the modern notion of median.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The median (in the context of probability) certainly appeared in the correspondence of Christiaan Huygens, but as an example of a statistic that was inappropriate for actuarial practice.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The earliest recommendation of the median dates to 1757, when Roger Joseph Boscovich developed a regression method based on the *L*1 norm and therefore implicitly on the median.
[src:quantile-regression/median] In 1774, Laplace made this desire explicit: he suggested the median be used as the standard estimator of the value of a posterior PDF.
[src:quantile-regression/median] The specific criterion was to minimize the expected magnitude of the error; $|\alpha -\alpha ^{*}|$ where $\alpha ^{*}$ is the estimate and $\alpha$ is the true value.
[src:quantile-regression/median] To this end, Laplace determined the distributions of both the sample mean and the sample median in the early 1800s.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Antoine Augustin Cournot in 1843 was the first to use the term *median* (*valeur médiane*) for the value that divides a probability distribution into two equal halves.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Gustav Theodor Fechner used the median (*Centralwerth*) in sociological and psychological phenomena.
[src:quantile-regression/median] It had earlier been used only in astronomy and related fields.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Gustav Fechner popularized the median into the formal analysis of data, although it had been used previously by Laplace, and the median appeared in a textbook by F.
[src:quantile-regression/median] Francis Galton used the term *median* in 1881, having earlier used the terms *middle-most value* in 1869, and the *medium* in 1880.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] In statistics, a **percentile** or **percentile score**, also known as **centile** (often denoted as $P_{k}$ or Pk, for a given percentage *k*), is a score greater than a given percentage of all scores (or data point value) in a sample.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] I.e., a score in the *k*-th percentile would be above approximately *k*% of all scores in its sample.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] For example, the 97th percentile (P97) is the value such that 97% of the data points are less than it.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Percentiles are a type of quantiles, obtained by a subdivision into 100 groups.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] The 25th percentile (P25) is also known as the first *quartile* (*Q*1), the 50th percentile (P50) as the *median* or second quartile (*Q*2), and the 75th percentile (P75) as the third quartile (*Q*3).
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] For example, the 50th percentile (median) is the score *below* (or *at or below*, depending on the definition) which 50% of the scores in the distribution are found.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Percentiles are expressed in the same unit of measurement as the input scores, *not* in percent; for example, if the scores refer to human weight, the corresponding percentiles will be expressed in kilograms or pounds.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] In the limit of an infinite sample size, the percentile approximates the *percentile function*, the inverse of the cumulative distribution function.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] A related quantity is the *percentile rank* of a given score, expressed as a percentage, which represents the fraction of scores in its distribution that are less than it, an exclusive definition.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Percentile scores and percentile ranks are often used in the reporting of test scores from norm-referenced tests, but, as just noted, they are not the same.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] For percentile ranks, a score is given and a percentage is computed.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Percentile ranks are exclusive: if the percentile rank for a specified score is 90%, then 90% of the scores were lower.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] In contrast, for percentiles a percentage is given and a corresponding score is determined, which can be either exclusive or inclusive.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] The score for a specified percentage (e.g., 90th) indicates a score below which (exclusive definition) or at or below which (inclusive definition) other scores in the distribution fall.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] There is no standard definition of percentile; however, all definitions yield similar results when the number of observations is very large and the probability distribution is continuous.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] In the limit, as the sample size approaches infinity, the 100*p*th percentile (0<*p*<1) approximates the inverse of the cumulative distribution function (CDF) thus formed, evaluated at *p*, as *p* approximates the CDF.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] This can be seen as a consequence of the Glivenko–Cantelli theorem.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Some methods for calculating the percentiles are given below.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] The methods given in the *calculation methods* section (below) are approximations for use in small-sample statistics.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] In general terms, for very large populations following a normal distribution, percentiles may often be represented by reference to a normal curve plot.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] The normal distribution is plotted along an axis scaled to standard deviations, or sigma ( $\sigma$ ) units.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Mathematically, the normal distribution extends to negative infinity on the left and positive infinity on the right.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Note, however, that only a very small proportion of individuals in a population will fall outside the −3*σ* to +3*σ* range.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] For example, with human heights very few people are above the +3*σ* height level.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Percentiles represent the area under the normal curve, increasing from left to right.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Each standard deviation represents a fixed percentile.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Thus, rounding to two decimal places, −3*σ* is the 0.13th percentile, −2*σ* the 2.28th percentile, −1*σ* the 15.87th percentile, 0*σ* the 50th percentile (both the mean and median of the distribution), +1*σ* the 84.13rd percentile, +2*σ* the 97.72nd percentile, and +3*σ* the 99.87th percentile.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] This is related to the 68–95–99.7 rule or the three-sigma rule.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Note that in theory the 0th percentile falls at negative infinity and the 100th percentile at positive infinity, although in many practical applications, such as test results, natural lower and/or upper limits are enforced.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] When Internet service provider bill "burstable" internet bandwidth, the 95th or 98th percentile usually cuts off the top 5% or 2% of bandwidth peaks in each month, and then bills at the nearest rate.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] In this way, infrequent peaks are ignored, and the customer is charged in a fairer way.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] The reason this statistic is so useful in measuring data throughput is that it gives a very accurate picture of the cost of the bandwidth.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] The 95th percentile says that 95% of the time, the usage is below this amount: so, the remaining 5% of the time, the usage is above that amount.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Physicians will often use infant and children's weight and height to assess their growth in comparison to national median and other percentiles which are found in growth charts.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] The 85th percentile speed of traffic on a road is often used as a guideline in setting speed limits and assessing whether such a limit is too high or low.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] In finance, value at risk is a standard measure to assess (in a model-dependent way) the quantity under which the value of the portfolio is not expected to sink within a given period of time and given a confidence value.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] There are many formulas or algorithms for a percentile score.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Hyndman and Fan identified nine and most statistical and spreadsheet software use one of the methods they describe.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Algorithms either return the value of a score that exists in the set of scores (nearest-rank methods) or interpolate between existing scores and are either exclusive or inclusive.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] The figure shows a 10-score distribution, illustrates the percentile scores that result from these different algorithms, and serves as an introduction to the examples given subsequently.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] The simplest are nearest-rank methods that return a score from the distribution, although compared to interpolation methods, results can be a bit crude.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] The Nearest-Rank Methods table shows the computational steps for exclusive and inclusive methods.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Interpolation methods, as the name implies, can return a score that is between scores in the distribution.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Algorithms used by statistical programs typically use interpolation methods, for example, the percentile.exc and percentile.inc functions in Microsoft Excel.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] The Interpolated Methods table shows the computational steps.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] One definition of percentile, often given in texts, is that the *P*-th percentile $(0<P\leq 100)$ of a list of *N* ordered values (sorted from least to greatest) is the smallest value in the list such that at least *P* percent of the data is less than or equal to that value.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] This is calculated by first calculating the ordinal rank and then taking the value from the ordered list that corresponds to that rank.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] The CDF method was described, e.g. by Langford.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] An alternative to rounding used in many applications is to use linear interpolation between adjacent ranks.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] , where $\lfloor x\rfloor$ uses the floor function to represent the integral part of x, whereas $x{\bmod {1}}$ uses the mod function to represent its fractional part (the remainder after division by 1).
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] As we can see, x is the continuous version of the subscript i, linearly interpolating v between adjacent nodes.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] There are two ways in which the variant approaches differ.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] The second way in which the variants differ is in the definition of the function near the margins of the $[0,1]$ range of p: $f(p,N)$ should produce, or be forced to produce, a result in the range $[1,N]$ , which may mean the absence of a one-to-one correspondence in the wider region.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] One author has suggested a choice of $C={\tfrac {1}{2}}(1+\xi )$ where ξ is the shape of the Generalized extreme value distribution which is the extreme value limit of the sampled distribution.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] [Source: Some software packages, including NumPy and Microsoft Excel (up to and including version 2013 by means of the PERCENTILE.INC function).
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Note that the $x\leftrightarrow p$ relationship is one-to-one for $p\in [0,1]$ , the only one of the three variants with this property; hence the "INC" suffix, for *inclusive*, on the Excel function.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] (The primary variant recommended by NIST.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Adopted by Microsoft Excel since 2010 by means of PERCENTIL.EXC function.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] In addition to the percentile function, there is also a *weighted percentile*, where the percentage in the total weight is counted instead of the total number.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] There is no standard function for a weighted percentile.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] One method extends the above approach in a natural way.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] Suppose we have positive weights $w_{1},w_{2},w_{3},\dots ,w_{N}$ associated, respectively, with our *N* sorted sample values.
[src:quantile-regression/percentile] The 50% weighted percentile is known as the weighted median.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] One advantage of quantile regression relative to ordinary least squares regression is that the quantile regression estimates are more robust against outliers in the response measurements.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] However, the main attraction of quantile regression goes beyond this and is advantageous when conditional quantile functions are of interest.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Different measures of central tendency and statistical dispersion can be used to more comprehensively analyze the relationship between variables.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] In ecology, quantile regression has been proposed and used as a way to discover more useful predictive relationships between variables in cases where there is no relationship or only a weak relationship between the means of such variables.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] The need for and success of quantile regression in ecology has been attributed to the complexity of interactions between different factors leading to data with unequal variation of one variable for different ranges of another variable.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Another application of quantile regression is in the areas of growth charts, where percentile curves are commonly used to screen for abnormal growth.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] The idea of estimating a median regression slope, a major theorem about minimizing sum of the absolute deviances and a geometrical algorithm for constructing median regression was proposed in 1760 by Ruđer Josip Bošković, a Jesuit Catholic priest from Dubrovnik.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] He was interested in the ellipticity of the earth, building on Isaac Newton's suggestion that its rotation could cause it to bulge at the equator with a corresponding flattening at the poles.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] He finally produced the first geometric procedure for determining the equator of a rotating planet from three observations of a surface feature.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] More importantly for quantile regression, he was able to develop the first evidence of the least absolute criterion and preceded the least squares introduced by Legendre in 1805 by fifty years.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Other thinkers began building upon Bošković's idea such as Pierre-Simon Laplace, who developed the so-called "methode de situation." This led to Francis Edgeworth's plural median - a geometric approach to median regression - and is recognized as the precursor of the simplex method.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] The works of Bošković, Laplace, and Edgeworth were recognized as a prelude to Roger Koenker's contributions to quantile regression.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Median regression computations for larger data sets are quite tedious compared to the least squares method, for which reason it has historically generated a lack of popularity among statisticians, until the widespread adoption of computers in the latter part of the 20th century.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Quantile regression expresses the conditional quantiles of a dependent variable as a linear function of the explanatory variables.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Crucial to the practicality of quantile regression is that the quantiles can be expressed as the solution of a minimization problem, as we will show in this section before discussing conditional quantiles in the next section.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Let Y be a real-valued random variable with cumulative distribution function $F_{Y}(y)=P(Y\leq y)$ .
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] where $0<\tau <1$ , $\mathbb {I} (\cdot )$ is an indicator function.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] The intuition is that for higher quantiles ( $\tau >0.5$ ), we penalize the positive residuals more than negative residuals, and vice versa, and the loss is unsymmetric.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] However, for $\tau =0.5$ the penalization is symmetric (hence, this results in a median estimator).
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] A specific quantile can be found by minimizing the expected loss of $Y-u$ with respect to u :(pp.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] If the solution $q_{\tau }$ is not unique, then we have to take the infimum of all such solutions to obtain the $\tau$ th quantile of the random variable *Y*.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Let Y be a discrete random variable that takes values $y_{i}=i$ with $i=1,2,\dots ,9$ with equal probabilities.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] The task is to find the median of Y, and hence the value $\tau =0.5$ is chosen.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Since ${0.5/9}$ is a constant, it can be taken out of the expected loss function (this is only true if $\tau =0.5$ ).
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Suppose that *u* is increased by 1 unit.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Then the expected loss will be changed by $(3)-(6)=-3$ on changing *u* to 4.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] and any change in *u* will increase the expected loss.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] The Table below shows the expected loss (divided by ${0.5/9}$ ) for different values of *u*.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Consider $\tau =0.5$ and let *q* be an initial guess for $q_{\tau }$ .
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] In order to minimize the expected loss, we move the value of *q* a little bit to see whether the expected loss will rise or fall.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] The first term of the equation is $F_{Y}(q)$ and second term of the equation is $1-F_{Y}(q)$ .
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Therefore, the change of expected loss function is negative if and only if $F_{Y}(q)<0.5$ , that is if and only if *q* is smaller than the median.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Similarly, if we reduce *q* by 1 unit, the change of expected loss function is negative if and only if *q* is larger than the median.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] In order to minimize the expected loss function, we would increase (decrease) *q* if *q* is smaller (larger) than the median, until *q* reaches the median.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] The idea behind the minimization is to count the number of points (weighted with the density) that are larger or smaller than *q* and then move *q* to a point where *q* is larger than $100\tau$ % of the points.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] where the function $\rho _{\tau }$ is the tilted absolute value function.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] The intuition is the same as for the population quantile.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] We use a capital Q to denote the conditional quantile to indicate that it is a random variable.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Solving the sample analog gives the estimator of $\beta$ .
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Note that when $\tau =0.5$ , the loss function $\rho _{\tau }$ is proportional to the absolute value function, and thus median regression is the same as linear regression by least absolute deviations.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] The mathematical forms arising from quantile regression are distinct from those arising in the method of least squares.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] The method of least squares leads to a consideration of problems in an inner product space, involving projection onto subspaces, and thus the problem of minimizing the squared errors can be reduced to a problem in numerical linear algebra.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Simplex methods or interior point methods can be applied to solve the linear programming problem.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Direct estimation of the asymptotic variance-covariance matrix is not always satisfactory.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Inference for quantile regression parameters can be made with the regression rank-score tests or with the bootstrap methods.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] See invariant estimator for background on invariance or see equivariance.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] The linear model $Q_{Y|X}(\tau )=X\beta _{\tau }$ mis-specifies the true systematic relation $Q_{Y|X}(\tau )=f(X,\tau )$ when $f(\cdot ,\tau )$ is nonlinear.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] However, $Q_{Y|X}(\tau )=X\beta _{\tau }$ minimizes a weighted distanced to $f(X,\tau )$ among linear models.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Furthermore, the slope parameters $\beta _{\tau }$ of the linear model can be interpreted as weighted averages of the derivatives $\nabla f(X,\tau )$ so that $\beta _{\tau }$ can be used for causal inference.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Specifically, the hypothesis $H_{0}:\nabla f(x,\tau )=0$ for all x implies the hypothesis $H_{0}:\beta _{\tau }=0$ , which can be tested using the estimator ${\hat {\beta _{\tau }}}$ and its limit distribution.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Because quantile regression does not normally assume a parametric likelihood for the conditional distributions of Y|X, the Bayesian methods work with a working likelihood.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] A convenient choice is the asymmetric Laplacian likelihood, because the mode of the resulting posterior under a flat prior is the usual quantile regression estimates.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] The posterior inference, however, must be interpreted with care.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Yang, Wang and He provided a posterior variance adjustment for valid inference.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] In addition, Yang and He showed that one can have asymptotically valid posterior inference if the working likelihood is chosen to be the empirical likelihood.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Beyond simple linear regression, there are several machine learning methods that can be extended to quantile regression.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] A switch from the squared error to the tilted absolute value loss function (a.k.a. the *pinball loss*) allows gradient descent-based learning algorithms to learn a specified quantile instead of the mean.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] It means that we can apply all neural network and deep learning algorithms to quantile regression, which is then referred to as nonparametric quantile regression.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Tree-based learning algorithms are also available for quantile regression (see, e.g., Quantile Regression Forests, as a simple generalization of Random Forests).
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] If the response variable is subject to censoring, the conditional mean is not identifiable without additional distributional assumptions, but the conditional quantile is often identifiable.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] This is the censored quantile regression model: estimated values can be obtained without making any distributional assumptions, but at the cost of computational difficulty, some of which can be avoided by using a simple three step censored quantile regression procedure as an approximation.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] For random censoring on the response variables, the censored quantile regression of Portnoy (2003) provides consistent estimates of all identifiable quantile functions based on reweighting each censored point appropriately.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] Censored quantile regression has close links to survival analysis.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile-regression] The quantile regression loss needs to be adapted in the presence of heteroscedastic errors in order to be efficient.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] In statistics and probability, **quantiles** are cut points dividing the range of a probability distribution into continuous intervals with equal probabilities or dividing the observations in a sample in the same way.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Common quantiles have special names, such as *quartiles* (four groups), *deciles* (ten groups), and *percentiles* (100 groups).
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The groups created are termed halves, thirds, quarters, etc., though more often the terms for the quantile are used for the groups created, rather than for the cut points.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] As in the computation of, for example, standard deviation, the estimation of a quantile depends upon whether one is operating with a statistical population or with a sample drawn from it.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] For a population, of discrete values or for a continuous population density, the k-th q-quantile is the data value where the cumulative distribution function crosses *k*/*q*.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] For a finite population of N equally probable values indexed 1, …, *N* from lowest to highest, the k-th q-quantile of this population can equivalently be computed via the value of Ip = *N* *k*/*q*.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] If Ip is not an integer, then round up to the next integer to get the appropriate index; the corresponding data value is the k-th q-quantile.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] On the other hand, if Ip is an integer then any number from the data value at that index to the data value of the next index can be taken as the quantile, and it is conventional (though arbitrary) to take the average of those two values (see Estimating quantiles from a sample).
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] If, instead of using integers k and q, the "p-quantile" is based on a real number p with 0 < *p* < 1 then p replaces *k*/*q* in the above formulas.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] This broader terminology is used when quantiles are used to parameterize continuous probability distributions.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Moreover, some software programs (including Microsoft Excel) regard the minimum and maximum as the 0th and 100th percentile, respectively.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] However, this broader terminology is an extension beyond traditional statistics definitions.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The following two examples use the Nearest Rank definition of quantile with rounding.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] For an explanation of this definition, see percentiles.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] What are the 4-quantiles (the "quartiles") of this dataset?
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] If also required, the zeroth quartile is 3 and the fourth quartile is 20.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] In particular, the median (*p* = *k*/*q* = 1/2) is never more than one standard deviation from the mean.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The above formula can be used to bound the value *μ* + *zσ* in terms of quantiles.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] When *z* ≤ 0, there is instead an upper bound $\mu +z\sigma \leq Q\left({\frac {1}{1+z^{2}}}\right)\,,\mathrm {~for~} z\leq 0.$ For example, the value *μ* + *zσ* for *z* = −3 will never exceed *Q*(*p* = 0.1), the first decile.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] One problem which frequently arises is estimating a quantile of a (very large or infinite) population based on a finite sample of size N.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Modern statistical packages rely on a number of techniques to estimate the quantiles.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Hyndman and Fan compiled a taxonomy of nine algorithms used by various software packages.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] All methods compute Qp, the estimate for the p-quantile (the k-th q-quantile, where *p* = *k*/*q*) from a sample of size N by computing a real valued index h.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] When h is an integer, the h-th smallest of the N values, xh, is the quantile estimate.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Otherwise a rounding or interpolation scheme is used to compute the quantile estimate from h, *x*⌊*h*⌋, and *x*⌈*h*⌉.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] (For notation, see floor and ceiling functions).
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The first three are piecewise constant, changing abruptly at each data point, while the last six use linear interpolation between data points, and differ only in how the index h used to choose the point along the piecewise linear interpolation curve, is chosen.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Mathematica, Matlab, R and GNU Octave programming languages support all nine sample quantile methods.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] SAS includes five sample quantile methods, SciPy and Maple both include eight, EViews and Julia include the six piecewise linear functions, Stata includes two, Python includes two, and Microsoft Excel includes two.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Mathematica, SciPy and Julia support arbitrary parameters for methods which allow for other, non-standard, methods.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The Google Guava Java library provides the type 7 scheme in the Quantiles class.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Of the techniques, Hyndman and Fan recommend R-8, but most statistical software packages have chosen R-6 or R-7 as the default.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The standard error of a quantile estimate can in general be estimated via the bootstrap.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The Maritz–Jarrett method can also be used.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The sample median is the most examined one amongst quantiles, being an alternative to estimate a location parameter, when the expected value of the distribution does not exist, and hence the sample mean is not a meaningful estimator of a population characteristic.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Moreover, the sample median is a more robust estimator than the sample mean.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] where *f*(*xp*) is the value of the distribution density at the p-th population quantile ( $x_{p}=F^{-1}(p)$ ).
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] But when the distribution is discrete, then the distribution of the sample median and the other quantiles fails to be Normal (see examples in https://stats.stackexchange.com/a/86638/28746).
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The definition of sample quantiles through the concept of mid-distribution function can be seen as a generalization that can cover as special cases the continuous distributions.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] For discrete distributions the sample median as defined through this concept has an asymptotically Normal distribution, see Ma, Y., Genton, M.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Asymptotic properties of sample quantiles of discrete distributions.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Annals of the Institute of Statistical Mathematics, 63(2), 227–243.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Computing approximate quantiles from data arriving from a stream can be done efficiently using compressed data structures.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The most popular methods are t-digest and KLL.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] These methods read a stream of values in a continuous fashion and can, at any time, be queried about the approximate value of a specified quantile.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Both algorithms are based on a similar idea: compressing the stream of values by summarizing identical or similar values with a weight.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] If the stream is made of a repetition of 100 times v1 and 100 times v2, there is no reason to keep a sorted list of 200 elements, it is enough to keep two elements and two counts to be able to recover the quantiles.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] With more values, these algorithms maintain a trade-off between the number of unique values stored and the precision of the resulting quantiles.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Some values may be discarded from the stream and contribute to the weight of a nearby value without changing the quantile results too much.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The t-digest maintains a data structure of bounded size using an approach motivated by *k*-means clustering to group similar values.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The KLL algorithm uses a more sophisticated "compactor" method that leads to better control of the error bounds at the cost of requiring an unbounded size if errors must be bounded relative to p.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Both methods belong to the family of *data sketches* that are subsets of Streaming Algorithms with useful properties: t-digest or KLL sketches can be combined.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Computing the sketch for a very large vector of values can be split into trivially parallel processes where sketches are computed for partitions of the vector in parallel and merged later.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The algorithms described so far directly approximate the empirical quantiles without any particular assumptions on the data, in essence the data are simply numbers or more generally, a set of items that can be ordered.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] These algorithms are computer science derived methods.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Another class of algorithms exist which assume that the data are realizations of a random process.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] These are statistics derived methods, sequential nonparametric estimation algorithms in particular.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] There are a number of such algorithms such as those based on stochastic approximation or Hermite series estimators.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] These statistics based algorithms typically have constant update time and space complexity, but have different error bound guarantees compared to computer science type methods and make more assumptions.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The statistics based algorithms do present certain advantages however, particularly in the non-stationary streaming setting i.e. time-varying data.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The algorithms of both classes, along with some respective advantages and disadvantages have been recently surveyed.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Standardized test results are commonly reported as a student scoring "in the 80th percentile", for example.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] This uses an alternative meaning of the word percentile as the *interval* between (in this case) the 80th and the 81st scalar percentile.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] This separate meaning of percentile is also used in peer-reviewed scientific research articles.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The meaning used can be derived from its context.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] If a distribution is symmetric, then the median is the mean (so long as the latter exists).
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] But, in general, the median and the mean can differ.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] For instance, with a random variable that has an exponential distribution, any particular sample of this random variable will have roughly a 63% chance of being less than the mean.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] This is because the exponential distribution has a long tail for positive values but is zero for negative numbers.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Quantiles are useful measures because they are less susceptible than means to difficulties created by long-tailed distributions and outliers.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Empirically, if the data being analyzed are not actually distributed according to an assumed distribution, or if there are other potential sources for outliers that are far removed from the mean, then quantiles may be more useful descriptive statistics than means and other moment-related statistics.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Closely related is the subject of least absolute deviations, a method of regression that is more robust to outliers than is least squares, in which the sum of the absolute value of the observed errors is used in place of the squared error.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The connection is that the mean is the single estimate of a distribution that minimizes expected squared error while the median minimizes expected absolute error.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Least absolute deviations shares the ability to be relatively insensitive to large deviations in outlying observations, although even better methods of robust regression are available.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] The quantiles of a random variable are preserved under increasing transformations, in the sense that, for example, if m is the median of a random variable X, then 2*m* is the median of 2*X*, unless an arbitrary choice has been made from a range of values to specify a particular quantile.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] (See quantile estimation, above, for examples of such interpolation.) Quantiles can also be used in cases where only ordinal data are available.
[src:quantile-regression/quantile] Values that divide sorted data into equal subsets other than four have different names.
